{
  "masechta": "Meilah",
  "daf": 6,
  "amud": "a-b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction to Me'ilah Status Changes and the Role of Zrika vs. Kabbala",
      "display_title": "Zrika vs. Kabbala",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Overview of Me'ilah status by sacrifice type and the effect of zrika",
          "display_title": "Me'ilah by Kodashim",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The debate over whether zrika or kabbala is the critical moment for status change",
          "display_title": "Critical Moment",
          "timestamp": "01:03"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Baraita on Notar: When There Is and Is Not Me'ilah",
      "display_title": "Notar Cases",
      "timestamp": "02:25",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon's teaching: some notar has me'ilah, some does not",
          "display_title": "Notar Distinction",
          "timestamp": "02:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "Simple reading: the critical moment is whether the problem (lina) occurred before or after zrika",
          "display_title": "Before/After Zrika",
          "timestamp": "02:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's alternative reading: the critical moment is really about heit lizrika (fitness for zrika), not zrika itself",
          "display_title": "Heit Lizrika",
          "timestamp": "03:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara questions why the baraita emphasizes zrika rather than shkiya (sunset) as the dividing line",
          "display_title": "Why Zrika?",
          "timestamp": "05:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's resolution: interpreting zrika as heit lizrika (fitness for zrika) rather than literal zrika",
          "display_title": "Reinterpreting Zrika",
          "timestamp": "07:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Baraita on Pigul: Applying the Same Logic to Disqualified Sacrifices",
      "display_title": "Pigul Cases",
      "timestamp": "10:46",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon's parallel teaching about pigul: some pigul has me'ilah, some does not",
          "display_title": "Pigul Distinction",
          "timestamp": "10:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "The problem: pigul cannot occur after zrika, so how can we understand 'after zrika' in this context?",
          "display_title": "Pigul Timing Problem",
          "timestamp": "11:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rashi's reading: interpreting the statement as referring to when one ate the meat, not when pigul occurred",
          "display_title": "Rashi's Interpretation",
          "timestamp": "11:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternative understanding: pigul before versus during zrika; even if pigul occurs after kabbala, the zrika must be good to help",
          "display_title": "Pigul and Zrika",
          "timestamp": "13:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's challenge: if the critical moment is really kabbala, why does the baraita emphasize zrika?",
          "display_title": "Challenge to Kabbala",
          "timestamp": "15:48"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's response: interpreting 'before zrika' and 'after zrika' as 'before it was fit for zrika' and 'after it was fit for zrika'",
          "display_title": "Reinterpreted Timing",
          "timestamp": "18:11"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gemara's Key Distinction: Going Into Me'ilah vs. Leaving Me'ilah",
      "display_title": "Into vs. Out of Me'ilah",
      "timestamp": "20:09",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Gemara's question: why does the baraita run to the case of kodashim kalim to demonstrate no me'ilah, rather than offering a case within kodashei kodashim?",
          "display_title": "Why Kodashim Kalim?",
          "timestamp": "20:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's answer: the baraita teaches that questionable or non-standard zrika can remove something from the me'ilah category more easily than it can add something to it",
          "display_title": "Asymmetry Principle",
          "timestamp": "22:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conceptual principle: standards may differ depending on whether one is trying to enter or exit the me'ilah category",
          "display_title": "Bidirectional Standards",
          "timestamp": "24:30"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Yotzei (Taken Outside): Rabbi Eliezer vs. Rabbi Akiva",
      "display_title": "Yotzei Debate",
      "timestamp": "40:46",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Parallel case in kodashim kalim: meat of imurim taken outside before zrika",
          "display_title": "Yotzei in Kalim",
          "timestamp": "40:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's analysis: why both cases were needed to teach that standards might differ based on direction (entering vs. exiting me'ilah)",
          "display_title": "Both Cases Needed",
          "timestamp": "42:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mishna: meat of kodashei kodashim taken outside before zrika; Rabbi Eliezer says there is me'ilah",
          "display_title": "Yotzei in Kodashim",
          "timestamp": "42:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Eliezer's position: yotzei is a disqualification that prevents zrika from changing status",
          "display_title": "Eliezer's View",
          "timestamp": "43:20"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva's counterargument from the case of two chatasim: if blood of one can permit meat of another (as one unit), surely blood should permit its own meat",
          "display_title": "Two Chatasim Case",
          "timestamp": "44:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva's position: yotzei is less serious than other disqualifications; zrika is effective even with yotzei",
          "display_title": "Akiva's View",
          "timestamp": "44:17"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Yochanan's Limitation on Rabbi Akiva's Position",
      "display_title": "Yochanan's Limitation",
      "timestamp": "47:01",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yochanan restricts Rabbi Akiva: zrika helps for yotzei only if some of the meat remains inside",
          "display_title": "Partial vs. Total Yotzei",
          "timestamp": "47:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "If all the meat went outside, even Rabbi Akiva agrees zrika is not effective",
          "display_title": "Complete Removal",
          "timestamp": "47:40"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Introduction to Pigul with Non-Existent Objects",
      "display_title": "Avud and Saruph",
      "timestamp": "47:49",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Assi reports from Babylonian colleagues: pigul thought can attach to meat/imurim that have been lost (avud) or burned (saruph)",
          "display_title": "Pigul on Nothing",
          "timestamp": "47:49"
        },
        {
          "title": "Even though the object does not exist, the pigul thought is still meaningful and affects the korban",
          "display_title": "Efficacy of Thought",
          "timestamp": "48:41"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
